<section xml:id="C16.S7">
<title>Relations to Other Functions</title>        
  
<para xml:id="C16.S7.p1">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="1" xml:id="C16.S7.p1.s1">
For orthogonal polynomials see Chapter 18.
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="2" sentence-num-in-section="2" xml:id="C16.S7.p1.s2">
For <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C16.S7.p1.m1">\mathit{3j}</Math> , <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C16.S7.p1.m2">\mathit{6j}</Math> , <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C16.S7.p1.m3">\mathit{9j}</Math> symbols see Chapter 34.
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="3" sentence-num-in-section="3" xml:id="C16.S7.p1.s3">
Further representations of special functions in terms of <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C16.S7.p1.m4">{{}_{p}F_{q}}</Math> functions are given inLuke (1969a, §§6.2–6.3), and an extensive list of <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C16.S7.p1.m5">{{}_{q+1}F_{q}}</Math> functions with rational numbers as parameters is given inKrupnikov and Kölbig (1997).
</sentence>

</para>
 
